type="user">jms-00WU</fr:addr><fr:route>jms-00WU.xml</fr:route><fr:title
text="New syntax for set operations">New syntax for set operations</fr:title></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>Intersections of queries are formed using a <fr:em>variadic</fr:em> constructor <fr:code><![CDATA[\query/isect]]></fr:code>. For example, the following computes the intersection of the queries <fr:code>q1</fr:code>, <fr:code>q2</fr:code>, and <fr:code>q3</fr:code>:</fr:p><fr:pre><![CDATA[\query/isect{q1}{q2}{q3}]]></fr:pre><fr:p>Unions of queries are formed similarly using the variadic <fr:code><![CDATA[\query/union]]></fr:code> constructor. The complement of a query <fr:code>q</fr:code> is written <fr:code><![CDATA[\query/compl{q}]]></fr:code>.</fr:p><fr:p><fr:strong>Note:</fr:strong> as before, to render the results of a query you must use the <fr:code><![CDATA[\query]]></fr:code> command; for example:</fr:p><fr:pre><![CDATA[\query{
 \query/isect{q1}{q2}{q3}
}]]></fr:pre></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree><fr:tree
show-metadata="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link
href="jonmsterling.xml"
title="Jon Sterling"
addr="jonmsterling"
type="local">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:date><fr:year>2024</fr:year><fr:month>6</fr:month><fr:day>20</fr:day></fr:date><fr:anchor>6530</fr:anchor><fr:addr
type="user">jms-00WV</fr:addr><fr:route>jms-00WV.xml</fr:route><fr:title
text="Query operations are first-class values">Query operations are first-class values</fr:title></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>Previously, the built-in query operations were written like <fr:code><![CDATA[\query/and]]></fr:code>, etc.; these names, however, were hard-coded into the lexer which meant that they did not work in the expected way with <fr:link
href="jms-005P.xml"
title="Forester"
addr="jms-005P"
type="local">Forester</fr:link>’s hierarchical namespacing. This hardcoding has been removed, and query operations are treated as first-class values that are resolved from primitive names in the <fr:code><![CDATA[\query/]]></fr:code> namespace. As such, the following code is equivalent to <fr:code><![CDATA[\query/compl{\query/taxon{theorem}}]]></fr:code>:</fr:p><fr:pre><![CDATA[\scope{
 \open\query
 \compl{\taxon{theorem}}
}]]></fr:pre><fr:p>A further consequence of this change is that queries can be defined compositionally by macros.</fr:p></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree><fr:tree
