href="jonmsterling.xml"
title="Jon Sterling"
addr="jonmsterling"
type="local">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:date><fr:year>2024</fr:year><fr:month>6</fr:month><fr:day>20</fr:day></fr:date><fr:anchor>6537</fr:anchor><fr:addr
type="user">jms-00WW</fr:addr><fr:route>jms-00WW.xml</fr:route><fr:title
text="Relational queries">Relational queries</fr:title></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>The most significant user-facing change to the query language is the ability to form basic <fr:em>relational</fr:em> queries along several <fr:link
href="jms-00WX.xml"
title="Built-in relation symbols"
addr="jms-00WX"
type="local">built-in relation-symbols</fr:link>; in fact, the built-in query constructors <fr:code><![CDATA[\query/taxon]]></fr:code>, <fr:code><![CDATA[\query/tag]]></fr:code>, and <fr:code><![CDATA[\query/author]]></fr:code> are all expressible in these terms.</fr:p><fr:tree
show-metadata="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link
href="jonmsterling.xml"
title="Jon Sterling"
addr="jonmsterling"
type="local">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:date><fr:year>2024</fr:year><fr:month>6</fr:month><fr:day>20</fr:day></fr:date><fr:anchor>6531</fr:anchor><fr:addr
type="user">jms-00WX</fr:addr><fr:route>jms-00WX.xml</fr:route><fr:title
text="Built-in relation symbols">Built-in relation symbols</fr:title></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p><fr:link
href="jms-005P.xml"
title="Forester"
addr="jms-005P"
type="local">Forester</fr:link> includes several built-in relation symbols, maintained as graphs that are accumulated during evaluation:</fr:p><fr:ul><fr:li><fr:code><![CDATA[\rel/transclusion]]></fr:code> contains an edge from <fr:code>x</fr:code> to <fr:code>y</fr:code> when <fr:code>x</fr:code> directly transcludes <fr:code>y</fr:code>, i.e. contains <fr:code><![CDATA[\transclude{y}]]></fr:code>.</fr:li>
    <fr:li><fr:code><![CDATA[\rel/links]]></fr:code> contains an edge from <fr:code>x</fr:code> to <fr:code>y</fr:code> when <fr:code>x</fr:code> links to <fr:code>y</fr:code>, i.e. contains something like <fr:code><![CDATA[[...](y)]]></fr:code> or <fr:code><![CDATA[[[y]]]]></fr:code>.</fr:li>
    <fr:li><fr:code><![CDATA[\rel/taxa]]></fr:code> contains an edge from <fr:code>x</fr:code> to <fr:code>y</fr:code> when <fr:code>x</fr:code> has taxon <fr:code>y</fr:code>, i.e. contains <fr:code><![CDATA[\taxon{y}]]></fr:code>.</fr:li>
    <fr:li><fr:code><![CDATA[\rel/tags]]></fr:code> contains an edge from <fr:code>x</fr:code> to <fr:code>y</fr:code> when <fr:code>x</fr:code> has tag <fr:code>y</fr:code>, i.e. contains <fr:code><![CDATA[\tag{y}]]></fr:code>.</fr:li>
    <fr:li><fr:code><![CDATA[\rel/authors]]></fr:code> contains an edge from <fr:code>x</fr:code> to <fr:code>y</fr:code> when <fr:code>x</fr:code> has author <fr:code>y</fr:code>, i.e. contains <fr:code><![CDATA[\author{y}]]></fr:code>.</fr:li>
    <fr:li><fr:code><![CDATA[\rel/contributors]]></fr:code> contains an edge from <fr:code>x</fr:code> to <fr:code>y</fr:code> when <fr:code>x</fr:code> is a tree with contributor <fr:code>y</fr:code>, i.e. contains <fr:code><![CDATA[\contributor{y}]]></fr:code>.</fr:li></fr:ul><fr:p>The implementation supports arbitrarily many relation symbols; this is not yet exposed to the user, but could in the future be employed by advanced users of <fr:link
href="jms-005P.xml"
title="Forester"
addr="jms-005P"
type="local">Forester</fr:link> to support the development of sophisticated ontologies.</fr:p></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree><fr:tree
