type="user">jms-00SP</fr:addr><fr:route>jms-00SP.xml</fr:route><fr:title
text="Forester 4.1 › changed behaviour of queries"><fr:link
href="jms-00S9.xml"
title="Forester 4.1"
addr="jms-00S9"
type="local">Forester 4.1</fr:link> › changed behaviour of queries</fr:title></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>Forester’s <fr:link
href="jms-0066.xml"
title="Forester 2.2 › queries"
addr="jms-0066"
type="local">rudimentary support for queries</fr:link> has been simplified somewhat. Previously, the results of a query would be gathered and, if non-empty, placed underneath an anonymous subtree (whose title could be modified using <fr:link
href="jms-0067.xml"
title="Forester 2.2 › flexible transclusion options"
addr="jms-0067"
type="local">transclusion options</fr:link>).</fr:p><fr:p>In light of the <fr:link
href="jms-00O4.xml"
title="Forester 3.1 › inline subtrees"
addr="jms-00O4"
type="local">user-level support for anonymous subtrees</fr:link> introduced in <fr:link
href="jms-00HY.xml"
title="Forester 3.1"
addr="jms-00HY"
type="local">Forester 3.1</fr:link>, the behaviour of queries has been simplified: the results of a query are simply transcluded directly without being enclosed in a subtree.</fr:p><fr:p>Although the new behaviour is simpler, it is no longer possible to have a query subtree that is hidden when it returns no results. Users should treat the querying feature as highly provisional, and subject to change and even potential removal.</fr:p></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree><fr:tree
